<paragraph id="86E4BF3285205621AE26B06FCC80EE3D" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C47CEE453674D95DB0D6C0B5D6E8393D" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="1BF51C0F94664D1C3C8CA9016978D6DE" authorityName="Jost, Oleas &amp; Meerow" authorityYear="2015" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis ruthiana" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="ruthiana">
<emphasis id="651D897D239CCDA8AC479D71DB08516C" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis ruthiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known from the type locality and a private reserve in southern Ecuador (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0333DF8C91A6E3A4227D7757077995B5" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Eucharis ruthiana. A Plant in cultivation B-C Leaves B Adaxial view C Abaxial view D-H Flowers D Upper portion of inflorescence showing flower habit E Flower cut and spread to show staminal corona F Dorsal-ventral view of limb showing the spread of the androecium G Lateral view H Lateral view with three tepals removed to show androecium I Ovary dissected to show numerous, superposed, globose ovules J Distribution of Eucharis ruthiana in Ecuador (black stars). Map courtesy of www. freeworldmaps. net." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.48.4399.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/41393" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">3I</figureCitation>
), in lower montane rain forest where it grows on stony soil in the understory of dense forest at ca. 1100 m elevation. A large population occurs on the Copalinga private reserve near Zamora according to the property owner.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="505918934A25C2A740D05DD3E5D8BA7F" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="17E4CC5916E52F5EEC190D672D394D76" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="361D03A7690EAB543FA180D0718F93D0" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">The species is named in honor of the late Ruth Moore, ardent supporter of conservation efforts in Ecuador.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AF4D4DF9FDDAAEB4D4F77C7EBFD18B27" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="notes">
<paragraph id="ECA52D5E648DD8A3C7CD7C81823DD592" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="07E54BF865285F55B313C42BD7A02B4F" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="90C36FFD98FEA4E58F508AFF41042ED1" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis (Heterocharis) subsp. subg." order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="subGenus" species="ruthiana" subGenus="Heterocharis" subSpecies="subg.">Eucharis subg. Heterocharis</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation id="14FE2882BCE771910C3F9BFAB49D087C" author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="136 - 220" publicationUrl="10.2307/2399347" refId="B5" refString="Meerow, AW, 1989. Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 136 - 220, DOI: 10.2307/2399347" title="Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2399347" volume="76" year="1989">Meerow (1989)</bibRefCitation>
, even though it appeared paraphyletic in his cladistic analysis of morphological characters. The large, fragrant flowers; numerous ovules per locule, and mature green fruits were considered symplesiomorphic for the genus. The subgenus previously included only two fertile species, 
<taxonomicName id="2A2592B3771E78AF8B460333F65BD73F" authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1883" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis sanderi" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="sanderi">
<emphasis id="5E5E2A5678F9E7DC2428F66EEB7823F2" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis sanderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<bibRefCitation id="FE16D4B20DCBCC944960FE116FA4E658" author="Baker, JG" journalOrPublisher="Curtis's Botanical Magazine" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="B1" refString="Baker, JG, 1883. Eucharis sanderi. Curtis's Botanical Magazine 109" title="Eucharis sanderi." volume="109" year="1883">Baker (1883)</bibRefCitation>
, endemic to the 
<normalizedToken id="C20C8976F1F7AA2076D1C50CE60E297F" originalValue="Chocó">Choco</normalizedToken>
region of Colombia, and 
<taxonomicName id="4EF28243AD5DB51BB106087EB6B8C5C8" authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis id="4996B66F014FD80C5EEE5BEF69E1D085" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Baker) 
<bibRefCitation id="77C9FD6BDF3C8B29504E99CE2C488689" author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Sida" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="29 - 49" refId="B3" refString="Meerow, AW, 1987a. New species of Phaedranassa and Eucharis (Amaryllidaceae). Sida 12: 29 - 49" title="New species of Phaedranassa and Eucharis (Amaryllidaceae)." volume="12" year="1987 a">Meerow (1987a)</bibRefCitation>
, found on both the eastern and western declivities of the Ecuadorean Andes. The group also contains two apparently sterile taxa, 
<taxonomicName id="971DD77C5B5D70414C19F9115A6520CE" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis grandiflora" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="grandiflora">
Eucharis 
<normalizedToken id="DB04731707D66E6A53FC2EFCFD857513" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
grandiflora
</taxonomicName>
Planch. &amp; Lind. (1853), a putative hybrid of 
<taxonomicName id="8A29D58E5AF4BABB342F454E5D569E68" authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis id="9F42ED95CBF7A70611FFB83CEDA33DE4" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C514D3DE830B076F87E1A689907FB3B6" authorityName="Baker" authorityYear="1883" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis sanderi" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="sanderi">
<emphasis id="1DB38C0760D49AA60948C046C9BACA3F" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis sanderi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, found in southern Colombia and northern Ecuador (
<bibRefCitation id="652522CBEC2C3D336335E5A639EDB3A4" author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="136 - 220" publicationUrl="10.2307/2399347" refId="B5" refString="Meerow, AW, 1989. Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 76: 136 - 220, DOI: 10.2307/2399347" title="Systematics of the Amazon lilies, Eucharis and Caliphruria (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2399347" volume="76" year="1989">Meerow 1989</bibRefCitation>
), most often in cultivation, and 
<taxonomicName id="53CB013186C32A6642333862D1D5C0E2" authorityName="Linden ex Planch" authorityYear="1857" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis amazonica" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="amazonica">
<emphasis id="5A2A7B2938515826AFD01057C3695F2C" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis amazonica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lind. ex Planch. (
<bibRefCitation id="E3C217EDF629B329CD1B11FB2721948B" author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="416 - 422" publicationUrl="10.2307/1220981" refId="B8" refString="Meerow, AW, Dehgan, B, 1984. Re-establishment and lectotypification of Eucharis amazonica Linden ex Planchon (Amaryllidaceae). Taxon 33: 416 - 422, DOI: 10.2307/1220981" title="Re-establishment and lectotypification of Eucharis amazonica Linden ex Planchon (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/1220981" volume="33" year="1984">Meerow and Dehgan 1984</bibRefCitation>
). The latter, most commonly found in the lower Huallaga Valley of Peru, never sets seed, has a triploid-derived chromosome number (2 
<emphasis id="8C16FB774F90AB8DB303F7F35722B426" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">n</emphasis>
= 68), and impaired pollen fertility (
<bibRefCitation id="C9C48189952715032D6EDE232CDE12A2" author="Nagalla, L" journalOrPublisher="Microbioscience Letters" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="89 - 94" refId="B11" refString="Nagalla, L, 1979. Cytological studies in Eucharis grandiflora Planch. and Linden. Microbioscience Letters 4: 89 - 94" title="Cytological studies in Eucharis grandiflora Planch. and Linden." volume="4" year="1979">Nagalla 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FC70D8FCD47559214CE6CA1B4CC6E2E7" author="Meerow, AW" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1559 - 1575" publicationUrl="10.2307/2444050" refId="B4" refString="Meerow, AW, 1987b. Chromosome cytology of Eucharis, Caliphruria, and Urceolina (Amaryllidaceae). American Journal of Botany 74: 1559 - 1575, DOI: 10.2307/2444050" title="Chromosome cytology of Eucharis, Caliphruria, and Urceolina (Amaryllidaceae)." url="10.2307/2444050" volume="74" year="1987 b">Meerow 1987b</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="560938390F60D38C37A00FE09430BB69" authorityName="Jost, Oleas &amp; Meerow" authorityYear="2015" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis ruthiana" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="ruthiana">
<emphasis id="F75E1D8E5DBD5554DE610AAD5B319793" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis ruthiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="670D445872EFA67A12753A87CD726A9D" authorityName="Meerow" authorityYear="1987" baseAuthorityName="Baker" class="Tentaculata" family="Amaryllidaceae" genus="Eucharis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Eucharis moorei" order="Asparagales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Ctenophora" rank="species" species="moorei">
<emphasis id="71DC83956A84D9795D17D1812840FEF7" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Eucharis moorei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but is easily separable (Table 
<tableCitation id="C4A890040FC314B3EBD99A5333B4BC5F" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Contrasting features of Eucharis ruthiana and Eucharis moorei." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" tableUuid="E4C8D089BB739D0F973740919AFAC572">2</tableCitation>
) by the narrower leaves and tepals, the deeply cleft staminal cup with long marginal teeth, the short, nearly filiform, incurved free filaments, and the relatively short style.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
